In France, voting is traditionally a low-tech experience: voters isolate themselves in a cabin and put a preprinted sheet of paper on which the candidate of their choice is registered in an envelope.
After the officials have confirmed the voter’s identity, the voter throws the envelope into the ballot box and signs the voter list.
The French electoral law sets the course quite strictly.
Since 1988, ballot boxes must be transparent so that voters and observers can testify that there are no envelopes at the beginning of the election and that no envelopes are cast, except those of the properly counted and authorized voters.
Candidates can send representatives who attend each part of the process as witnesses, and in the evening the votes of volunteers are counted under strict supervision and by special procedures.
