If a small group of living beings (a small population) is separated from the main population from which it originates (for example, if they move over a mountain chain or a river, or if they move to a new so that they cannot easily return), they will often find themselves in a different environment than before.
This new environment has other resources and other competitors, so the new population needs other features or adjustments to be a strong competitor than what it previously needed.
The original population has not changed at all, and it still needs the same adjustments as before.
Over time, the new population begins to adapt to its new environment, and then it looks less and less like the other population.
After thousands or even millions of years, two populations then look so different that they can no longer be assigned to the same species.
This process is called specialization, which simply means the emergence of new species, which is an inevitable consequence and a very important part of evolution.
