Technological determinism is a term that encompasses a wide range of ideas in practice, from technology push or technological imperative to the strict sense that human fate is determined by an underlying logic associated with scientific laws and their manifestation in technology.
Most interpretations of technological determinism share two general ideas: on the one hand that the development of technology itself follows a path that is largely beyond cultural or political influence, and on the other hand that technology in turn has “effects” on societies that are more inherently than socially conditioned.
One could say that the passenger car is essential to the development of roads.
However, a nationwide road network is economically incapable for a small number of cars, so new production methods are being developed to reduce the cost of car seating.
The widespread automobile ownership also leads to a higher number of accidents on the roads, which in turn leads to the invention of new techniques in the healthcare sector to repair damaged bodies.
